colnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Selston, Nottinghamshire, England":"Selston, Nottinghamshire, England"},"en":{"about 1110–about 1200":"about 1110–about 1200","1110–1200":"1110–1200","1110–Male":"1110–Deceased","1140–1230":"1140–1230","1080–Male":"1080–Deceased","1087–1200":"1087–1200","1080":"1080","about 1140":"about 1140","1135":"1135","1200":"1200","1110":"1110","1087":"1087","1230":"1230","about 1200":"about 1200","1140":"1140","about 1110":"about 1110","1109":"1109","Normandie, France":"Normandy, France","Le Chesnay, Eure, Upper Normandy, France":"Le Chesnay, Eure, Upper Normandy, France","Edwardstone, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Edwardstone, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Selston, Nottinghamshire, England":"Selston, Nottinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes De Montchesney was born about 1110, in Le Chesnay, Eure, Upper Normandy, France, her father, Antigonus de Montchesney, was 32 and her mother, Agnes de Weynes, was 25. She married Richard de Holbrook de Brahamb in 1135, in Lincolnshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She lived in Lincolnshire, England in 1139. She died about 1200, in Selston, Nottinghamshire, England, at the age of 92."},"et":{"about 1110–about 1200":"umbes 1110–umbes 1200","1110–1200":"1110–1200","1110–Male":"1110–Surnud","1140–1230":"1140–1230","1080–Male":"1080–Surnud","1087–1200":"1087–1200","1080":"1080","about 1140":"umbes 1140","1135":"1135","1200":"1200","1110":"1110","1087":"1087","1230":"1230","about 1200":"umbes 1200","1140":"1140","about 1110":"umbes 1110","1109":"1109","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Le Chesnay, Eure, Upper Normandy, France":"Le Chesnay, Eure, Haute-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Edwardstone, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Edwardstone, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Selston, Nottinghamshire, England":"Selston, Nottinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1110–about 1200":"noin 1110–noin 1200","1110–1200":"1110–1200","1110–Male":"1110–Kuollut","1140–1230":"1140–1230","1080–Male":"1080–Kuollut","1087–1200":"1087–1200","1080":"1080","about 1140":"noin 1140","1135":"1